        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>197 Seventh<lb/>
               19&#47;7&#47;82<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S Morais
                My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I can now<lb/> write you as I have desired&#44;<lb/> concerning my late uncle.<lb/></p>
            <p>When I heard he<lb/> was coming I rejoiced to think<lb/> that we might meet and all<lb/> three talk over matters.<lb/></p>
            <p>But his strict orders<lb/> not to receive even calls forbade<lb/> me hoping for an immediate<lb/> conference&#58; and he himself<lb/> requested me to keep his presence<lb/> in New York a secret&#44; lest<lb/> his needed rest should be<lb/> disturbed.<lb/></p>
            <p>He &#91;&#63;&#93; to improve&#44; but<lb/> then again he seemed to<lb/> retropen&#91;&#63;&#93;&#44; and last Friday night<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>fortnight came the sudden charge.<lb/>  That night he had spoken as cheerily<lb/> as usual to me&#44; greeting me&#44; and<lb/> next morning they had great<lb/> difficulty in covering him.  He<lb/> was continually sleepy and<lb/> tho&#39; I got him up&#44; he sat quiet<lb/> hardly noticing conversation&#44;<lb/> and evidently unable to keep his<lb/> mind to a subject.  He twice asked<lb/> me the name of the book <del>he</del> I had<lb/> in my hand&#44; and when I suggested<lb/> it was time for him to go to bed<lb/> again&#44; he said he could go<lb/> himself without aid&#44; in a<lb/> tone which showed that he had<lb/> misunderstood me&#44; and not<lb/> at all as if resenting my<lb/> suggestion.<lb/></p>
            <p>I make these observations to<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>3.<lb/></p>
            <p>show you how his mind<lb/> was gradually losing<lb/> its powers.<lb/></p>
            <p>He soon began to speak<lb/> inarticulately&#44; next day he<lb/> was roused into consciousness<lb/> only now and then<lb/> and grew weaker and<lb/> weaker until Monday<lb/> night about 9.5 pm<lb/> his spirit passed away<lb/> almost <sic>imperceptably</sic>.<lb/>  I accompanied remains<lb/> and officiated until the<lb/> &#91;&#63;&#93; was up<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>4.<lb/></p>
            <p>But I must heartily apologize<lb/> that any error of mine should<lb/> have put you to the annoyance<lb/> you experienced.  If I omitted<lb/> about place of funeral it was<lb/> my forgetfulness and I can only<lb/> think of the excitement of the time<lb/> or an excuse&#44; matters for funeral<lb/> having been left in my hands<lb/> The loss to ourselves through his<lb/> death is boundless&#44; what we are<lb/> to do I know not&#59; only in our very<lb/> helplessness I take courage knowing<lb/> that when human efforts fail<lb/> then Divine aid comes.<lb/></p>
            <p>I find much work has accumulated<lb/> and I wish to prepare for lecture<lb/> next Sabbath&#44;&#45;&#45;the reason I begin so long<lb/> before is that it will be in Herald and<lb/> I intend to preach upon restoration&#45;&#45;<lb/> historically&#44; commercially &#38;c considered. Yrs H. P. M.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>Rev S Morais<lb/>
                546 North 5th<lb/>
                Philad.<lb/>
                Pa.<lb/></p>
                
                <p>for Rev H. P. Mendes<lb/></p>
        </body>
